            <entry xml:id="entry_cad" xml:lang="os">
                <form xml:lang="os-x-iron" type="lemma"><orth>cad</orth></form>
                <form xml:lang="os-x-digor" type="dialectal"><orth>cadæ</orth></form>
                <sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                        <q>озеро</q>
                    </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                        <q>lake</q>
                    </abv:tr></sense>
                <re>
                    <form xml:lang="os-x-iron" type="lemma"><orth>ænæbyn cad</orth></form>
                    <form xml:lang="os-x-digor" type="dialectal"><orth>ænæbun cadæ</orth></form>
                    <sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>бездонное озеро</q>
                        </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>depthless lake</q>
                        </abv:tr></sense>
                </re>
                <abv:exampleGrp>
                    <abv:example>
                        <quote>abyrǵytæ baftydysty Qely cadmæ</quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>абреки попали к Кельскому озеру</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>abreks arrived to Keli Lake</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                    </abv:example>
                    <abv:example>
                        <quote>æxsyry cady īw x˳y ī, æmæ myn ūj igærtæ ærxæssut</quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>в молочном озере есть один кабан, так принесите мне его печень</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>there is one boar in the milk lake, so bring me his liver</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Munk."/><biblScope>52</biblScope></bibl>
                    </abv:example>
                </abv:exampleGrp>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Общеиранское слово, в других иранских языках
                    засвидетельствованное в значении ‘колодец’: <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>čah</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ps"><lang/>
                        <w>tsāh</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="x-balochi"><lang/>
                        <w>čāϑ</w><note type="comment" xml:lang="ru"> (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                                    target="#ref_BSOS"/><biblScope>VIII
                            139</biblScope></bibl>)</note></mentioned>, <mentioned
                        xml:lang="sog"><lang/>
                        <w>*čāt(č't)</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="kho"><lang/>
                        <w>tcāta</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>čāt-</w></mentioned>. Может быть, сюда же <mentioned xml:lang="ydg"><lang/>
                        <w>čād-</w>
                        <gloss><q>орошать</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Morgenstierne._IIFL"/><biblScope>II
                    201</biblScope></bibl>). Значение ‘озеро’ находим в <mentioned xml:lang="khw"><lang/>
                        <w>čat</w></mentioned>, представляющем старое заимствование из
                    восточноиранского (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Morgenstierne._Rep._Afgh."
                        /><biblScope>76</biblScope></bibl>). Ос. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_cʼaj"
                    /> ‘колодец’ представляет то же самое слово, но прошедшее иной путь: из
                    персидского оно проникло в грузинский, а оттуда — в осетинский. <mentioned
                        xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>čāh</w></mentioned> восходит к *čāϑa-, <mentioned xml:lang="os"><lang/>
                        <w>cad</w></mentioned> — к %ičāta%i-. — Вероятно, от корня %ikan%i-
                    ‘копать’. — <mentioned xml:lang="kbd"><lang/>
                        <w>šät’ät’</w>
                        <gloss><q>озеро</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="kbd"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>болото</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Ногма"/><biblScope>221</biblScope></bibl>) — из
                            аланского?%n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"
                            /><biblScope>II 78</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>51</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref
                            type="bibl" target="#ref_ВЯ"/><biblScope>1952 V
                    63</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">A common Iranian word, which is atessted in other languages in
                    the meaning ‘well’: <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>čah</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ps"><lang/>
                        <w>tsāh</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="x-balochi"><lang/>
                        <w>čāϑ</w><note type="comment" xml:lang="en">
                                    (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_BSOS"/><biblScope>VIII
                                    139</biblScope></bibl>)</note></mentioned>, <mentioned
                        xml:lang="sog"><lang/>
                        <w>*čāt(č't)</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="kho"><lang/>
                        <w>tcāta</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>čāt-</w></mentioned>. May be <mentioned xml:lang="ydg"><lang/>
                        <w>čād-</w>
                        <gloss><q>орошать</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Morgenstierne._IIFL"/><biblScope>II 201</biblScope></bibl>)
                    also refers here. The meaning ‘lake’ is found in <mentioned xml:lang="khw"><lang/>
                        <w>čat</w></mentioned> representing an old borrowing from East Iranian
                            (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Morgenstierne._Rep._Afgh."
                            /><biblScope>76</biblScope></bibl>). Ossetic <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_cʼaj"/> ‘well’ represents the same word, but that has passed
                    through a different route: from Persian it penetrated into Georgian, and from
                    there into Ossetic. <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>čāh</w></mentioned> traces back to *čāϑa-, <mentioned xml:lang="os"><lang/>
                        <w>cad</w></mentioned> — to %ičāta%i-. — Probably, it is derived from the
                    root %ikan%i- ‘dig’. — <mentioned xml:lang="kbd"><lang/>
                        <w>šät’ät’</w>
                        <gloss><q>lake</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="kbd"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>swamp</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Ногма"/><biblScope>221</biblScope></bibl>) — from
                            Alan?%n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"
                            /><biblScope>II 78</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>51</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref
                            type="bibl" target="#ref_ВЯ"/><biblScope>1952 V
                    63</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
